# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rtp-streaming
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] A **codec** is a computer hardware or software component that encodes or decodes a data stream or signal.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] *Codec* is a portmanteau of **coder/decoder**.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] In electronic communications, an **endec** is a device that acts as both an encoder and a decoder on a signal or data stream, and hence is a type of codec.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] *Endec* is a portmanteau of **encoder/decoder**.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] A coder or encoder encodes a data stream or a signal for transmission or storage, possibly in encrypted form, and the decoder function reverses the encoding for playback or editing.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Codecs are used in videoconferencing, streaming media, and video editing applications.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Originally, in the mid-20th century, a codec was a hardware device that coded analog signals into digital form using pulse-code modulation (PCM).
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Later, the term was also applied to software for converting between digital signal formats, including companding functions.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] An audio codec converts analog audio signals into digital signals for transmission or encodes them for storage.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] A receiving device converts the digital signals back to analog form using an audio decoder for playback.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] An example of this is the codecs used in the sound cards of personal computers.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] A video codec accomplishes the same task for video signals.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] When implementing the Infrared Data Association (IrDA) protocol, an endec may be used between the UART and the optoelectronic systems.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Examples of hardware codecs include Intel QSV and Azalia Audio; examples of software codecs include FFmpeg (and its Libavcodec).
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] In addition to encoding a signal, a codec may also compress the data to reduce transmission bandwidth or storage space.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Compression codecs are classified primarily into lossy codecs and lossless codecs.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Lossless codecs are often used for archiving data in compressed form while retaining all information present in the original stream.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] If preserving the original quality of the stream is more important than eliminating the correspondingly larger data sizes, lossless codecs are preferred.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Using more than one codec or encoding scheme successively can also degrade quality significantly.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] The decreasing cost of storage capacity and network bandwidth has a tendency to reduce the need for lossy codecs for some media.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] They reduce quality in order to maximize compression.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Often, this type of compression is virtually indistinguishable from the original uncompressed sound or images, depending on the codec and the settings used.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] The most widely used lossy data compression technique in digital media is based on the discrete cosine transform (DCT), used in compression standards such as JPEG images, H.26x and MPEG video, and MP3 and AAC audio.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Smaller data sets ease the strain on relatively expensive storage sub-systems such as non-volatile memory and hard disk, as well as write-once-read-many formats such as CD-ROM, DVD, and Blu-ray Disc.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Lower data rates also reduce cost and improve performance when the data is transmitted, e.g., over the internet.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Two principal techniques are used in codecs, pulse-code modulation and delta modulation.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Codecs are often designed to emphasize certain aspects of the media to be encoded.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] For example, a digital video (using a DV codec) of a sports event needs to encode motion well but not necessarily exact colors, while a video of an art exhibit needs to encode color and surface texture well.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Audio codecs for cell phones need to have very low latency between source encoding and playback.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] In contrast, audio codecs for recording or broadcasting can use high-latency audio compression techniques to achieve higher fidelity at a lower bit rate.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] There are thousands of audio and video codecs, ranging in cost from free to hundreds of dollars or more.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] This variety of codecs can create compatibility and obsolescence issues.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] The impact is lessened for older formats, for which free or nearly-free codecs have existed for a long time.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] The older formats are often ill-suited to modern applications, however, such as playback on small portable devices.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] For example, raw uncompressed PCM audio (44.1 kHz, 16-bit stereo, as represented on an audio CD or in a .wav or .aiff file) has long been a standard across multiple platforms, but its transmission over networks is slow and expensive compared with more modern compressed formats, such as Opus and MP3.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Many multimedia data streams contain both audio and video, and often some metadata that permits synchronization of audio and video.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Each of these three streams may be handled by different programs, processes, or hardware, but for the multimedia data streams to be useful in stored or transmitted form, they must be encapsulated together in a container format.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Lower bitrate codecs allow more users, but they also have more distortion.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Beyond the initial increase in distortion, lower bit rate codecs also achieve their lower bit rates by using more complex algorithms that make certain assumptions, such as those about the media and the packet loss rate.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Other codecs may not make those same assumptions.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] When a user with a low bitrate codec talks to a user with another codec, additional distortion is introduced by each transcoding.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Audio Video Interleave (AVI) is sometimes erroneously described as a codec, but AVI is actually a container format, while a codec is a software or hardware tool that encodes or decodes audio or video into or from some audio or video format.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] Audio and video encoded with many codecs might be put into an AVI container, although AVI is not an ISO standard.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] There are also other well-known container formats, such as Ogg, ASF, QuickTime, RealMedia, Matroska, and DivX Media Format.
[src:rtp-streaming/codec] MPEG transport stream, MPEG program stream, MP4, and ISO base media file format are examples of container formats that are ISO standardized.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The **RTP Control Protocol** (**RTCP**) is a binary-encoded out-of-band signaling protocol that functions alongside the Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP).
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] RTCP provides statistics and control information for an RTP session.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] It partners with RTP in the delivery and packaging of multimedia data but does not transport any media data itself.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] An application may use this information to control quality of service parameters, perhaps by limiting flow, or using a different codec.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Typically, RTP will be sent on an even-numbered UDP port, with RTCP messages being sent over the next higher odd-numbered port.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] RTCP itself does not provide any flow encryption or authentication methods.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] RTCP reports are expected to be sent by all participants, even in a multicast session, which may involve thousands of recipients.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Such traffic will increase proportionally with the number of participants.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Thus, to avoid network congestion, the protocol must include session bandwidth management.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] This is achieved by dynamically controlling the frequency of report transmissions.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] RTCP bandwidth usage should generally not exceed 5% of the total session bandwidth.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Furthermore, 25% of the RTCP bandwidth should be reserved to media sources at all times, so that in large conferences, new participants can receive the CNAME identifiers of the senders without excessive delay.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The RTCP reporting interval is randomized to prevent unintended synchronization of reporting.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The recommended minimum RTCP report interval per station is 5 seconds.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Stations should not transmit RTCP reports more often than once every 5 seconds.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Identifies the version of RTP, which is the same in RTCP packets as in RTP data packets.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The version defined by this specification is two (2).
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Indicates if there are extra padding bytes at the end of the RTP packet.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Padding may be used to fill up a block of certain size, for example as required by an encryption algorithm.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The last byte of the padding contains the number of padding bytes that were added (including itself).
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The number of reception report blocks contained in this packet.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Contains a constant to identify RTCP packet type.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Indicates the length of this RTCP packet (including the header itself) in 32-bit units minus one.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] uniquely identifies the source of a stream.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Note that multiple reports can be concatenated into a single compound RTCP packet, each with its own packet header.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] RTCP distinguishes several types of packets: *sender report*, *receiver report*, *source description*, and *goodbye*.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] In addition, the protocol is extensible and allows application-specific RTCP packets.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] A standards-based extension of RTCP is the *extended report* packet type.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The sender report is sent periodically by the active senders in a conference to report transmission and reception statistics for all RTP packets sent during the interval.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The absolute timestamp allows the receiver to synchronize RTP messages.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] It is particularly important when both audio and video are transmitted simultaneously because audio and video streams use independent relative timestamps.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The receiver report is for passive participants, those that do not send RTP packets.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The report informs the sender and other receivers about the quality of service.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The Source Description message is used to send the CNAME item to session participants.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] It may also be used to provide additional information such as the name, e-mail address, telephone number, and address of the owner or controller of the source.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] A source sends a BYE message to shut down a stream.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] It allows an endpoint to announce that it is leaving the conference.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Although other sources can detect the absence of a source, this message is a direct announcement.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The application-specific message provides a mechanism to design application-specific extensions to the RTCP protocol.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] In large-scale applications, such as in Internet Protocol television (IPTV), very long delays (minutes to hours) between RTCP reports may occur, because of the RTCP bandwidth control mechanism required to control congestion (see § Protocol functions).
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Acceptable frequencies are usually less than one per minute.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] This affords the potential of inappropriate reporting of the relevant statistics by the receiver or causes evaluation by the media sender to be inaccurate relative to the current state of the session.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Methods have been introduced to alleviate the problems: RTCP filtering, RTCP biasing and hierarchical aggregation.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The Hierarchical Aggregation (or also known as RTCP feedback hierarchy) is an optimization of the RTCP feedback model and its aim is to shift the maximum number of users limit further together with quality of service (QoS) measurement.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The RTCP bandwidth is constant and takes just 5% of session bandwidth.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Therefore, the reporting interval about QoS depends, among others, on the number of session members, and for very large sessions, it can become very high (minutes or even hours).
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] However, the acceptable interval is about 10 seconds of reporting.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Bigger values would cause time-shifted and very inaccurate reported status about the current session status, and any optimization made by the sender could even have a negative effect on network or QoS conditions.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The Hierarchical Aggregation is used with Source-Specific Multicast where only a single source is allowed, i.e., IPTV.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Another type of multicast could be Any-Source Multicast, but it is not so suitable for large-scale applications with a huge number of users.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] As of June 2007, only the most modern IPTV systems use Hierarchical aggregation.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] Feedback Target is a new type of member that was first introduced by the Internet Draft draft-ietf-avt-rtcpssm-13.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The Hierarchical Aggregation method has extended its functionality.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-control-protocol] The function of this member is to receive Receiver Reports (RR) (see RTCP) and retransmit summarized RR packets, so-called Receiver Summary Information (RSI) to a sender (in case of single-level hierarchy).
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The **Real-time Transport Protocol** (**RTP**) is a network protocol for delivering audio and video over IP networks.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is used in communication and entertainment systems that involve streaming media, such as telephony, video teleconference applications including WebRTC, television services and web-based push-to-talk features.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP typically runs over User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is used in conjunction with the RTP Control Protocol (RTCP).
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] While RTP carries the media streams (e.g., audio and video), RTCP is used to monitor transmission statistics and quality of service (QoS) and aids synchronization of multiple streams.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is one of the technical foundations of voice over IP and in this context is often used in conjunction with a signaling protocol such as the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP), which establishes connections across the network.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP was developed by the Audio-Video Transport Working Group of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and first published in 1996 as RFC 1889, which was then superseded by RFC 3550 in 2003.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Research on audio and video over packet-switched networks dates back to the early 1970s.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) published RFC 741 in 1977 and began developing RTP in 1992, and would go on to develop Session Announcement Protocol (SAP), the Session Description Protocol (SDP), and the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP).
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is designed for end-to-end, real-time transfer of streaming media.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The protocol provides facilities for jitter compensation and detection of packet loss and out-of-order delivery, which are common, especially during UDP transmissions on an IP network.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP allows data transfer to multiple destinations through IP multicast.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is regarded as the primary standard for audio/video transport in IP networks and is used with an associated profile and payload format.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The design of RTP is based on the architectural principle known as application-layer framing, where protocol functions are implemented in the application as opposed to the operating system's protocol stack.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Real-time multimedia streaming applications require timely delivery of information and often can tolerate some packet loss to achieve this goal.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] For example, loss of a packet in an audio application may result in loss of a fraction of a second of audio data, which can be made unnoticeable with suitable error concealment algorithms.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), although standardized for RTP use, is not normally used in RTP applications because TCP favors reliability over timeliness.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Instead, the majority of the RTP implementations are built on the User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Other transport protocols specifically designed for multimedia sessions are SCTP and DCCP, although, as of 2012, they were not in widespread use.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP was developed by the Audio/Video Transport working group of the IETF standards organization.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is used in conjunction with other protocols such as H.323 and RTSP.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The RTP specification describes two protocols: RTP and RTCP.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is used for the transfer of multimedia data, and the RTCP is used to periodically send control information and QoS parameters.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The data transfer protocol, RTP, carries real-time data.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Information provided by this protocol includes timestamps (for synchronization), sequence numbers (for packet loss and reordering detection) and the payload format, which indicates the encoded format of the data.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The control protocol, RTCP, is used for quality of service (QoS) feedback and synchronization between the media streams.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The bandwidth of RTCP traffic compared to RTP is small, typically around 5%.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP sessions are typically initiated between communicating peers using a signaling protocol, such as H.323, the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP), RTSP, or Jingle (XMPP).
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] These protocols may use the Session Description Protocol to specify the parameters for the sessions.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] An RTP session is established for each multimedia stream.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Audio and video streams may use separate RTP sessions, enabling a receiver to selectively receive components of a particular stream.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The RTP and RTCP design is independent of the transport protocol.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Applications most typically use UDP with port numbers in the unprivileged range (1024 to 65535).
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP) and the Datagram Congestion Control Protocol (DCCP) may be used when a reliable transport protocol is desired.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The RTP specification recommends even port numbers for RTP and the use of the next odd port number for the associated RTCP session.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] A single port can be used for RTP and RTCP in applications that multiplex the protocols.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is used by real-time multimedia applications such as voice over IP, audio over IP, WebRTC, Internet Protocol television, and professional video over IP including SMPTE 2022 and SMPTE 2110.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is designed to carry a multitude of multimedia formats, which permits the development of new formats without revising the RTP standard.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] To this end, the information required by a specific application of the protocol is not included in the generic RTP header.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] For each class of application (e.g., audio, video), RTP defines a *profile* and associated *payload formats*.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Every instantiation of RTP in a particular application requires a profile and payload format specifications.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The profile defines the codecs used to encode the payload data and their mapping to payload format codes in the protocol field *Payload Type* (PT) of the RTP header.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Each profile is accompanied by several payload format specifications, each of which describes the transport of particular encoded data.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The mapping of MPEG-4 audio/video streams to RTP packets is specified in RFC 3016, and H.263 video payloads are described in RFC 2429.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP packets are created at the application layer and handed to the transport layer for delivery.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Each unit of RTP media data created by an application begins with the RTP packet header.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The RTP header has a minimum size of 12 bytes.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] After the header, optional header extensions may be present.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] This is followed by the RTP payload, the format of which is determined by the particular class of application.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Used to indicate if there are extra padding bytes at the end of the RTP packet.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Padding may be used to fill up a block of certain size, for example, as required by an encryption algorithm.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The extension header is application or profile specific.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Contains the number of CSRC identifiers (defined below) that follow the SSRC (also defined below).
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Signaling used at the application level in a profile-specific manner.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] If it is set, it means that the current data has some special relevance for the application.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Indicates the format of the payload and thus determines its interpretation by the application.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Values are profile specific and may be dynamically assigned.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Used by the receiver to play back the received samples at appropriate time and interval.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] When several media streams are present, the timestamps may be independent in each stream.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The granularity of the timing is application specific.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] For example, an audio application that samples data once every 125 μs (8 kHz, a common sample rate in digital telephony) would use that value as its clock resolution.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Video streams typically use a 90 kHz clock.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The clock granularity is one of the details that is specified in the RTP profile for an application.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The synchronization sources within the same RTP session will be unique.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] enumerate contributing sources to a stream that has been generated from multiple sources.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] indicates the length of the extension in 32-bit units, excluding the 32 bits of the extension header.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] A functional multimedia application requires other protocols and standards used in conjunction with RTP.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Protocols such as SIP, Jingle, RTSP, H.225 and H.245 are used for session initiation, control and termination.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] Other standards, such as H.264, MPEG and H.263, are used for encoding the payload data as specified by the applicable RTP profile.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] An RTP sender captures the multimedia data, then encodes, frames and transmits it as RTP packets with appropriate timestamps and increasing timestamps and sequence numbers.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The sender sets the *payload type* field in accordance with connection negotiation and the RTP profile in use.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] The RTP receiver detects missing packets and may reorder packets.
[src:rtp-streaming/real-time-transport-protocol] It decodes the media data in the packets according to the payload type and presents the stream to its user.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] The **Session Description Protocol** (**SDP**) is a format for describing multimedia communication sessions for the purposes of announcement and invitation.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Its predominant use is in support of streaming media applications, such as voice over IP (VoIP) and video conferencing.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] SDP does not deliver any media streams itself but is used between endpoints for negotiation of network metrics, media types, and other associated properties.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] The set of properties and parameters is called a *session profile*.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] SDP is extensible for the support of new media types and formats.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] SDP was originally a component of the Session Announcement Protocol (SAP), but found other uses in conjunction with the Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP), the Real-time Streaming Protocol (RTSP), Session Initiation Protocol (SIP), and as a standalone protocol for describing multicast sessions.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] The IETF published the original specification as a Proposed Standard in April 1998 (RFC 2327).
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Revised specifications were released in 2006 (RFC 4566), and in 2021 (RFC 8866).
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] The Session Description Protocol describes a session as a group of fields in a text-based format, one field per line.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Where `<character>` is a single case-sensitive character and `<value>` is structured text in a format that depends on the character.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed immediately to either side of the equal sign.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Session descriptions consist of three sections: session, timing, and media descriptions.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Each description may contain multiple timing and media descriptions.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Names are only unique within the associated syntactic construct.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Below is a sample session description from RFC 4566.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] This session is originated by the user "jdoe", at IPv4 address 10.47.16.5.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Its name is "SDP Seminar" and extended session information ("A Seminar on the session description protocol") is included along with a link for additional information and an email address to contact the responsible party, Jane Doe.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] This session is specified to last for two hours using NTP timestamps, with a connection address (which indicates the address clients must connect to or — when a multicast address is provided, as it is here — subscribe to) specified as IPv4 224.2.17.12 with a TTL of 127.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Recipients of this session description are instructed to only receive media.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Two media descriptions are provided, both using RTP Audio Video Profile.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] The first is an audio stream on port 49170 using RTP/AVP payload type 0 (defined by RFC 3551 as PCMU), and the second is a video stream on port 51372 using RTP/AVP payload type 99 (defined as "dynamic").
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Finally, an attribute is included which maps RTP/AVP payload type 99 to format h263-1998 with a 90 kHz clock rate.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] RTCP ports for the audio and video streams of 49171 and 51373, respectively, are implied.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] The SDP specification is purely a format for session description.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] It is intended to be distributed over different transport protocols as necessary, including SAP, SIP, and RTSP.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] SDP could even be transmitted by email or as an HTTP payload.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] SDP uses attributes to extend the core protocol.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Attributes can appear within the Session or Media sections and are scoped accordingly as *session-level* or *media-level*.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] New attributes are added to the standard occasionally through registration with IANA.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] The parameters *v*, *s*, and *o* are mandatory, must not be empty, and should be UTF-8-encoded.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] They are used as identifiers and are not intended to be displayed to users.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] A few other attributes are also present in the example, either as a session-level attribute (such as the attribute in property form *a=recvonly*), or as a media-level attribute (such as the attribute in value form *a=rtpmap:99 h263-1998/90000* for the video in the example).
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Absolute times are represented in Network Time Protocol (NTP) format (the number of seconds since 1900).
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] If the stop time is 0 then the session is *unbounded*.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] If the start time is also zero then the session is considered *permanent*.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Unbounded and permanent sessions are discouraged but not prohibited.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Intervals can be represented with NTP times or in typed time: a value and time units (days: *d*, hours: *h*, minutes: *m* and seconds: *s*) sequence.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] When repeat times are specified, the start time of each repetition may need to be adjusted to compensate for daylight saving time changes so that it will occur at the same local time in a specific time zone throughout the period between the start time and the stop time.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] All these offsets are relative to the start time, they are not cumulative.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] NTP supports this with field *z*, which indicates a series of pairs whose first item is the NTP absolute time when a daylight adjustment will occur, and the second item indicates the offset to apply relative to the absolute times computed with the field *r*.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] For example, if a daylight adjustment will subtract 1 hour on 31 October 2010 at 3 am UTC (i.e.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] If the weekly 1-hour session was repeated every Sunday for one full year, i.e. from Sunday 1 August 2010 3 am UTC to Sunday 26 June 2011 4 am UTC (stop time of the last repeat, i.e.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] As SDP announcements for repeated sessions should not be made to cover very long periods exceeding a few years, the number of daylight adjustments to include in the z= parameter should remain small.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] Sessions may be repeated irregularly over a week but scheduled the same way for all weeks in the period, by adding more tuples in the *r* parameter.
[src:rtp-streaming/session-description-protocol] The SDP protocol does not support repeating sessions monthly and yearly schedules with such simple repeat times, because they are irregularly spaced in time; instead, additional *t*/*r* tuples may be supplied for each month or year.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] While streaming is most commonly associated with multimedia from a remote server over the Internet, it also includes offline multimedia between devices on a local area network.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] For example, using DLNA and a home server, or in a personal area network between two devices using Bluetooth (which uses radio waves rather than IP).
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Online streaming was initially popularized by RealNetworks and Microsoft in the 1990s and has since grown to become the globally most popular method for consuming music and videos, with numerous competing subscription services being offered since the 2010s.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Audio streaming to wireless speakers, often using Bluetooth, is another use that has become prevalent during that decade.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Live streaming is the real-time delivery of content during production, much as live television broadcasts content via television channels.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Distinguishing delivery methods from the media applies specifically to, as most of the traditional media delivery systems are either inherently *streaming* (e.g., radio, television) or inherently *non-streaming* (e.g., books, videotapes, audio CDs).
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The term "streaming media" can apply to media other than video and audio, such as live closed captioning and real-time text, which are all considered "streaming text".
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The term "streaming" was first used for tape drives manufactured by Data Electronics Inc. that were meant to slowly ramp up and run for the entire track; slower ramp times lowered drive costs.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] "Streaming" was applied in the early 1990s as a better description for video on demand and later live video on IP networks.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] It was first done by Starlight Networks for video streaming and Real Networks for audio streaming.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Beginning in 1881, Théâtrophone enabled subscribers to listen to opera and theatre performances over telephone lines.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The concept of media streaming eventually came to America.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The Tel-musici service operated in Delaware from 1909 to 1914.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In the early 1920s, George Owen Squier was granted patents for a system for the transmission and distribution of signals over electrical lines, which was the technical basis for what later became *Muzak*, a technology for streaming continuous music to commercial customers without the use of radio.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The Telephone Music Service, a live jukebox service, began in 1929 and continued until 1997.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The clientele eventually included 120 bars and restaurants in the Pittsburgh area.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] A tavern customer would deposit money in the jukebox, use a telephone on top of the jukebox, and ask the operator to play a song.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The operator would find the record in the studio library of more than 100,000 records, put it on a turntable, and the music would be piped over the telephone line to play in the tavern.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The music media began as 78s, 33s and 45s, played on the six turntables they monitored.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] CDs and tapes were incorporated in later years.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The business had a succession of owners, notably Bill Purse, his daughter Helen Reutzel, and finally Dotti White.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The revenue stream for each quarter was split between 60% for the music service and 40% for the tavern owner.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] This business model eventually became unsustainable due to city permits and the cost of setting up these telephone lines.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Attempts to display media on computers date back to the earliest days of computing in the mid-20th century.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] However, little progress was made for several decades, primarily due to the high cost and limited capabilities of computer hardware.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] From the late 1980s through the 1990s, consumer-grade personal computers became powerful enough to display various media.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The primary technical issues related to streaming were having enough CPU and bus bandwidth to support the required data rates and achieving the real-time computing performance required to prevent buffer underruns and enable smooth streaming of the content.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] However, computer networks were still limited in the mid-1990s, and audio and video media were usually delivered over non-streaming channels, such as playback from a local hard disk drive or CD-ROMs on the end user's computer.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Terminology in the 1970s was at best confusing for applications such as telemetered aircraft or missile test data.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] By then PCM [Pulse Code Modulation] was the dominant transmission type.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] This PCM transmission was bit-serial and not packetized so the 'streaming' terminology was often a confusion factor.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In 1969 Grumman acquired one of the first telemetry ground stations [Automated Telemetry Station, 'ATS'] which had the capability for reconstructing serial telemetered data which had been recorded on digital computer peripheral tapes.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Computer peripheral tapes were inherently recorded in blocks.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Reconstruction was required for continuous display purposes without time-base distortion.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The Navy implemented similar capability in DoD for the first time in 1973.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] These implementations are the only known examples of true 'streaming' in the sense of reconstructing distortion-free serial data from packetized or blocked recordings.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] 'Real-time' terminology has also been confusing in streaming context.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The most accepted definition of 'real-time' requires that all associated processing or formatting of the data must take place prior to availability of the next sample of each measurement.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In the 1970s the most powerful mainframe computers were not fast enough for this task at significant overall data rates in the range of 50,000 samples per second.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] For that reason both the Grumman ATS and the Navy Real-time Telemetry Processing System [RTPS] employed unique special purpose digital computers dedicated to real-time processing of raw data samples.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In 1990, the first commercial Ethernet switch was introduced by Kalpana, which enabled the more powerful computer networks that led to the first streaming video solutions used by schools and corporations.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Practical streaming media was only made possible with advances in data compression due to the impractically high bandwidth requirements of uncompressed media.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Raw digital audio encoded with pulse-code modulation (PCM) requires a bandwidth of 1.4 Mbit/s for uncompressed CD audio, while raw digital video requires a bandwidth of 168 Mbit/s for SD video and over 1000 Mbit/s for FHD video.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] During the late 1990s and early 2000s, users had increased access to computer networks, especially the Internet.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] During the early 2000s, users had access to increased network bandwidth, especially in the last mile.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] These technological improvements facilitated the streaming of audio and video content to computer users in their homes and workplaces.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] There was also an increasing use of standard protocols and formats, such as TCP/IP, HTTP, and HTML, as the Internet became increasingly commercialized, which led to an infusion of investment into the sector.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The band Severe Tire Damage was the first group to perform live on the Internet.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] On 24 June 1993, the band was playing a gig at Xerox PARC, while elsewhere in the building, scientists were discussing new technology (the Mbone) for broadcasting on the Internet using multicasting.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] As proof of PARC's technology, the band's performance was broadcast and could be seen live in Australia and elsewhere.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] RealNetworks pioneered the broadcast of a baseball game between the New York Yankees and the Seattle Mariners over the Internet in 1995.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The first symphonic concert on the Internet—a collaboration between the Seattle Symphony and guest musicians Slash, Matt Cameron, and Barrett Martin—took place at the Paramount Theater in Seattle, Washington, on 10 November 1995.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In 1996, Marc Scarpa produced the first large-scale, online, live broadcast, the Adam Yauch–led Tibetan Freedom Concert, an event that would define the format of social change broadcasts.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Scarpa continued to pioneer in the streaming media world with projects such as Woodstock '99, Townhall with President Clinton, and more recently Covered CA's campaign "Tell a Friend Get Covered", which was livestreamed on YouTube.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Xing Technology was founded in 1989 and developed a JPEG streaming product called "StreamWorks".
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Another streaming product appeared in late 1992 and was named StarWorks.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] StarWorks enabled on-demand MPEG-1 full-motion videos to be randomly accessed on corporate Ethernet networks.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Starworks was from Starlight Networks, which also pioneered live video streaming on Ethernet and via Internet Protocol over satellites with Hughes Network Systems.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Other early companies that created streaming media technology include Progressive Networks and Protocomm prior to widespread World Wide Web usage.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] After the Netscape IPO in 1995 (and the release of Windows 95 with built-in TCP/IP support), usage of the Internet expanded, and many companies "went public", including Progressive Networks (which was renamed "RealNetworks", and listed on Nasdaq as "RNWK").
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] As the web became even more popular in the late 90s, streaming video on the internet blossomed from startups such as Vivo Software (later acquired by RealNetworks), VDOnet (acquired by RealNetworks), Precept (acquired by Cisco), and Xing (acquired by RealNetworks).
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Microsoft developed a media player known as ActiveMovie in 1995 that supported streaming media and included a proprietary streaming format, which was the precursor to the streaming feature later in Windows Media Player 6.4 in 1999.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In June 1999, Apple also introduced a streaming media format in its QuickTime 4 application.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] It was later also widely adopted on websites, along with RealPlayer and Windows Media streaming formats.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The competing formats on websites required each user to download the respective applications for streaming, which resulted in many users having to have all three applications on their computer for general compatibility.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In 2000, Industryview.com launched its "world's largest streaming video archive" website to help businesses promote themselves.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Webcasting became an emerging tool for business marketing and advertising that combined the immersive nature of television with the interactivity of the Web.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The ability to collect data and feedback from potential customers caused this technology to gain momentum quickly.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Around 2002, the interest in a single, unified, streaming format and the widespread adoption of Adobe Flash prompted the development of a video streaming format through Flash, which was the format used in Flash-based players on video hosting sites.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The first popular video streaming site, YouTube, was founded by Steve Chen, Chad Hurley, and Jawed Karim in 2005.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] It initially used a Flash-based player, which played MPEG-4 AVC video and AAC audio, but now defaults to HTML video.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Increasing consumer demand for live streaming prompted YouTube to implement a new live streaming service for users.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The company currently also offers a (secure) link that returns the available connection speed of the user.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] US streaming revenue grew 57 percent to $1.6 billion in the first half of 2016 and accounted for almost half of industry sales.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The term *streaming wars* was coined to describe the new era (starting in the late 2010s) of competition between video streaming services such as Netflix, Amazon Prime Video, Hulu, HBO Max, Disney+, Paramount+, Apple TV, Peacock, and many more.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The competition between increasingly popular online platforms, such as Netflix and Amazon, and legacy broadcasters and studios moving online, like Disney and NBC, has driven each service to find ways to differentiate from one another.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] A key differentiator has been offering exclusive content, often self-produced and created for a specific market segment.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] When Netflix first launched in 2007, it became one of the more dominant streaming platforms even though it initially offered no original content.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] It would be nearly six years before Netflix began offering its own shows, such as House of Cards, Orange Is the New Black, and Hemlock Grove.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The legacy services also began producing original digital-only content, but they also began restricting their back catalog of shows and movies to their platforms, one of the most notable examples being Disney+.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Disney took advantage of owning popular movies and shows like Frozen, Snow White, and the Star Wars and Marvel franchises, which could draw in more subscribers and make it a more serious competitor to Netflix and Amazon.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Research suggests that this approach to streaming competition can be disadvantageous for consumers by increasing spending across platforms, and for the industry as a whole by dilution of subscriber base.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Once specific content is made available on a streaming service, piracy searches for the same content decrease; competition or legal availability across multiple platforms appears to deter online piracy.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Exclusive content produced for subscription services such as Netflix tends to have a higher production budget than content produced exclusively for pay-per-view services, such as Amazon Prime Video.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] This competition increased during the first two years of the COVID-19 pandemic as more people stayed home and watched TV.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] "The COVID-19 pandemic has led to a seismic shift in the film & TV industry in terms of how films are made, distributed, and screened.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Many industries have been hit by the economic effects of the pandemic" (Totaro Donato).
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In August 2022, a CNN headline declared that "The streaming wars are over" as pandemic-era restrictions had largely ended and audience growth had stalled.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] This led services to focus on profit over market share by cutting production budgets, cracking down on password sharing, and introducing ad-supported tiers.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] A December 2022 article in *The Verge* echoed this, declaring an end to the "golden age of the streaming wars".
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In September 2023, several streaming services formed a trade association named the Streaming Innovation Alliance (SIA), spearheaded by Charles Rivkin of the Motion Picture Association (MPA).
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Former U.S. representative Fred Upton and former Federal Communications Commission (FCC) acting chair Mignon Clyburn serve as senior advisors.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Notably absent were Apple, Amazon, Roku, and Tubi.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Advances in computer networking, combined with powerful home computers and operating systems, have made streaming media affordable and easy for the public.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Stand-alone Internet radio devices emerged to offer listeners a non-technical option for listening to audio streams.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] These audio-streaming services became increasingly popular; music streaming reached 4 trillion streams globally in 2023—a significant increase from 2022—jumping 34% over the year.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In general, multimedia content is data-intensive, so media storage and transmission costs are still significant.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Media is generally compressed for transport and storage.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Increasing consumer demand for streaming high-definition (HD) content has led the industry to develop technologies such as WirelessHD and G.hn, which are optimized for streaming HD content.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Many developers have introduced HD streaming apps that work on smaller devices, such as tablets and smartphones, for everyday purposes.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] A media stream can be streamed either *live* or *on demand*.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Live streams are generally provided by a method called *true streaming*.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] True streaming sends the information straight to the computer or device without saving it to a local file.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] On-demand streaming is provided by a method called *progressive download*.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Progressive download saves the received information to a local file and then plays it from that location.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] On-demand streams are often saved to files for extended period of time, while live streams are available at one time only (e.g., during a football game).
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Streaming media is increasingly being coupled with the use of social media.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] For example, sites such as YouTube encourage social interaction in webcasts through features such as live chat, online surveys, user posting of comments online, and more.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Furthermore, streaming media is increasingly being used for social business and e-learning.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The Horowitz Research State of Pay TV, OTT, and SVOD 2017 report said that 70 percent of those viewing content did so through a streaming service and that 40 percent of TV viewing was done this way, twice the number from five years earlier.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Millennials, the report said, streamed 60 percent of the content.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] One of the movie streaming industry's largest impacts was on the DVD industry, which drastically dropped in popularity and profitability with the mass popularization of online content.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The rise of media streaming caused the downfall of many DVD rental companies, such as Blockbuster.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In July 2015, *The New York Times* published an article about Netflix's DVD services.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] It stated that Netflix was continuing their DVD services with 5.3 million subscribers, which was a significant drop from the previous year.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] On the other hand, their streaming service had 65 million members.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The shift to streaming platforms also led to the decline of DVD rental services.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In July 2024, NBC News reported that RedBox, a DVD rental service that had operated for 22 years, would shut down due to the rapid incline of streaming platforms.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] As the rental services has been rapidly declining since 2010, the business had to file for bankruptcy, with 99% of households now subscribing to streaming services.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Further reflecting the shift away from physical media, Best Buy has ceased selling DVDs.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Music streaming is one of the most popular ways in which consumers interact with streaming media.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In the age of digitization, the private consumption of music has transformed into a public good, largely due to one player in the market: Napster.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Napster, a peer-to-peer (P2P) file-sharing network where users could upload and download MP3 files freely, broke all music industry conventions when it launched in early 1999 in Hull, Massachusetts.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The platform was developed by Shawn and John Fanning as well as Sean Parker.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Not only did this development disrupt the music industry by making songs that previously required payment to be freely accessible to any Napster user, but it also demonstrated the power of P2P networks in turning any digital file into a public, shareable good.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] For the brief period of time that Napster existed, mp3 files fundamentally changed as a type of good.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Songs were no longer financially excludable, barring access to a computer with internet access, and they were not rivals, meaning if one person downloaded a song, it did not diminish another user from doing the same.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Napster, like most other providers of public goods, faced the free-rider problem.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Every user benefits when an individual uploads an mp3 file, but there is no requirement or mechanism that forces all users to share their music.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Generally, the platform encouraged sharing; users who downloaded files from others often had their own files available for upload as well.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] However, not everyone chose to share their files.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] There was no built-in incentive specifically discouraging users from sharing their own files.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] This structure revolutionized the consumer's perception of ownership over digital goods; it made music freely replicable.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Napster quickly garnered millions of users, growing faster than any other business in history.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] At the peak of its existence, Napster boasted about 80 million users globally.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The site gained so much traffic that many college campuses had to block access to Napster because it created network congestion from so many students sharing music files.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The advent of Napster sparked the creation of numerous other P2P sites, including LimeWire (2000), BitTorrent (2001), and the Pirate Bay (2003).
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The reign of P2P networks was short-lived.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Numerous lawsuits were filed against Napster by various record labels, all of which were subsidiaries of Universal Music Group, Sony Music Entertainment, Warner Music Group, or EMI.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In addition to this, the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA) also filed a lawsuit against Napster on the grounds of unauthorized distribution of copyrighted material, which ultimately led Napster to shut down in 2001.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Napster, Inc.* fundamentally changed the way consumers interact with music streaming.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] It was argued on 2 October 2000, and was decided on 12 February 2001.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit ruled that a P2P file-sharing service could be held liable for contributory and vicarious infringement of copyright, serving as a landmark decision for Intellectual property law.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The second claim by the plaintiffs was that Napster was actively contributing to copyright infringement since it had knowledge of widespread file sharing on its platform.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Since Napster took no action to reduce infringement and financially benefited from repeated use, the court ruled against the P2P site.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The injunction ordered against Napster ended the brief period in which music streaming was a public good – non-rival and non-excludable in nature.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Other P2P networks had some success at sharing MP3s, though they all met a similar fate in court.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The ruling set the precedent that copyrighted digital content cannot be freely replicated and shared unless given consent by the owner, thereby strengthening the property rights of artists and record labels alike.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Although music streaming is no longer a freely replicable public good, streaming platforms such as Spotify, Deezer, Apple Music, SoundCloud, YouTube Music, and Amazon Music have shifted music streaming to a club-type good.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] While some platforms, most notably Spotify, give customers access to a freemium service that enables the use of limited features for exposure to advertisements, most companies operate under a premium subscription model.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Under such circumstances, music streaming is financially excludable, requiring that customers pay a monthly fee for access to a music library, but non-rival, since one customer's use does not impair another's.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] An article written by The New York Times in 2021 states that "streaming saved music." This is because it provided monthly revenue.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Especially Spotify offers its free platform, but you can pay for their premium to get music ad-free.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] This allows access for people to stream music anywhere from their devices not having to rely on CDs anymore.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] There is competition between services similar but lesser to the streaming wars for video media.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] As of 2019, Spotify has over 207 million users in 78 countries, As of 2018, Apple Music has about 60 million, and SoundCloud has 175 million.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] All platforms provide varying degrees of accessibility.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Apple Music and Prime Music only offer their services for paid subscribers, whereas Spotify and SoundCloud offer freemium and premium services.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Napster, owned by Rhapsody since 2011, has resurfaced as a music streaming platform offering subscription-based services to over 4.5 million users as of January 2017.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In the evolving music streaming landscape, competition among platforms is shaped by various factors, including royalty rates, exclusive content, and market expansion strategies.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] A notable development occurred in January 2025, when Universal Music Group (UMG) and Spotify announced a new multi-year agreement.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] This partnership aims to enhance opportunities for artists and consumers through innovative subscription tiers and an enriched audio-visual catalog.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The music industry's response to music streaming was initially negative.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Along with music piracy, streaming services disrupted the market and contributed to the fall in US revenue from $14.6 billion in 1999 to $6.3 billion in 2009.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] CDs and single-track downloads were not selling because content was freely available on the Internet.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] By 2018, however, music streaming revenue exceeded that of traditional revenue streams (e.g. record sales, album sales, downloads).
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Streaming revenue is now one of the largest driving forces behind the growth in the music industry.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] By August 2020, the COVID-19 pandemic had streaming services busier than ever.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The pandemic contributed to a surge in subscriptions, in the UK alone, 12 million people joined a new streaming service that they had not previously had.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Global subscriptions skyrocketed passing 1 billion.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Within the first 3 months, back in 2020, nearly 15.7 million people signed up for Netflix.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The International Federation of the Phonographic Industry (IFPI) recompiled the music industry initiatives around the world related to the COVID-19.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In its State of the Industry report, it recorded that the global recorded music market grew by 7.4% in 2022, the 6th consecutive year of growth.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] This growth was driven by streaming, mostly from paid subscription streaming revenues which increased by 18.5%, fueled by 443 million users of subscription accounts by the end of 2020.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The COVID-19 pandemic has also driven an increase in misinformation and disinformation, particularly on streaming platforms like YouTube and podcasts.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Streaming also refers to the offline streaming of multimedia at home.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] This is made possible by technologies such as DLNA, which allow devices on the same local network to connect to each other and share media.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Such capabilities are heightened using network-attached storage (NAS) devices at home, or using specialized software like Plex Media Server, Jellyfin or TwonkyMedia.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] A broadband speed of 2 Mbit/s or more is recommended for streaming standard-definition video, for example to a Roku, Apple TV, Google TV or a Sony TV Blu-ray Disc Player.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] 5 Mbit/s is recommended for high-definition content and 25 Mbit/s for ultra-high-definition content.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Streaming media storage size is calculated from the streaming bandwidth and length of the media using the following formula (for a single user and file): storage size in megabytes is equal to length (in seconds) × bit rate (in bit/s) / (8 × 1024 × 1024).
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] For example, one hour of digital video encoded at 300 kbit/s (this was a typical broadband video in 2005 and it was usually encoded in 320 × 240 resolution) will be: (3,600 s × 300,000 bit/s) / (8 × 1024 × 1024) requires around 128 MB of storage.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] If the file is stored on a server for on-demand streaming and this stream is viewed by 1,000 people at the same time using a Unicast protocol, the requirement is 300 kbit/s × 1,000 = 300,000 kbit/s = 300 Mbit/s of bandwidth.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] This is equivalent to around 135 GB per hour.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Using a multicast protocol the server sends out only a single stream that is common to all users.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Therefore, such a stream would only use 300 kbit/s of server bandwidth.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In 2018 video was more than 60% of data traffic worldwide and accounted for 80% of growth in data usage.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Video and audio streams are compressed to make the file size smaller.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Audio coding formats include MP3, Vorbis, AAC and Opus.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Video coding formats include H.264, HEVC, VP8, VP9 and AV1.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Encoded audio and video streams are assembled in a container bitstream such as MP4, FLV, WebM, ASF or ISMA.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The bitstream is delivered from a streaming server to a streaming client (e.g., the computer user with their Internet-connected laptop) using a transport protocol, such as Adobe's RTMP or RTP.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In the 2010s, technologies such as Apple's HLS, Microsoft's Smooth Streaming, Adobe's HDS and non-proprietary formats such as MPEG-DASH emerged to enable adaptive bitrate streaming over HTTP as an alternative to using proprietary transport protocols.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Often, a streaming transport protocol is used to send video from an event venue to a cloud transcoding service and content delivery network, which then uses HTTP-based transport protocols to distribute the video to individual homes and users.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The streaming client (the end user) may interact with the streaming server using a control protocol, such as MMS or RTSP.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The quality of the interaction between servers and users is based on the workload of the streaming service; as more users attempt to access a service the quality may be affected by resource constraints in the service.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Deploying clusters of streaming servers is one such method where there are regional servers spread across the network, managed by a singular, central server containing copies of all the media files as well as the IP addresses of the regional servers.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] This central server then uses load balancing and scheduling algorithms to redirect users to nearby regional servers capable of accommodating them.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] This approach also allows the central server to provide streaming data to both users as well as regional servers using FFmpeg libraries if required, thus demanding the central server to have powerful data processing and immense storage capabilities.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In return, workloads on the streaming backbone network are balanced and alleviated, allowing for optimal streaming quality.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Designing a network protocol to support streaming media raises many problems.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Datagram protocols, such as the User Datagram Protocol (UDP), send the media stream as a series of small packets.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] This is simple and efficient; however, there is no mechanism within the protocol to guarantee delivery.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] It is up to the receiving application to detect loss or corruption and recover data using error correction techniques.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] If data is lost, the stream may suffer a dropout.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The Real-Time Streaming Protocol (RTSP), Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP) and the Real-time Transport Control Protocol (RTCP) were specifically designed to stream media over networks.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] RTSP runs over a variety of transport protocols, while the latter two are built on top of UDP.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] HTTP adaptive bitrate streaming is based on HTTP progressive download, but contrary to the previous approach, here the files are very small, so that they can be compared to the streaming of packets, much like the case of using RTSP and RTP.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Reliable protocols, such as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), guarantee correct delivery of each bit in the media stream.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] It means, however, that when there is data loss on the network, the media stream stalls while the protocol handlers detect the loss and retransmit the missing data.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Clients can minimize this effect by buffering data for display.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] While delay due to buffering is acceptable in video-on-demand scenarios, users of interactive applications such as video conferencing will experience a loss of fidelity if the delay caused by buffering exceeds 200 ms.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Unicast protocols send a separate copy of the media stream from the server to each recipient.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Unicast is the norm for most Internet connections but does not scale well when many users want to view the same television program concurrently.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Multicast protocols were developed to reduce server and network loads resulting from duplicate data streams that occur when many recipients receive unicast content streams independently.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] These protocols send a single stream from the source to a group of recipients.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Depending on the network infrastructure and type, multicast transmission may or may not be feasible.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] One potential disadvantage of multicasting is the loss of video on demand functionality.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Continuous streaming of radio or television material usually precludes the recipient's ability to control playback.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] However, this problem can be mitigated by elements such as caching servers, digital set-top boxes, and buffered media players.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] IP multicast provides a means to send a single media stream to a group of recipients on a computer network.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] A connection management protocol, usually Internet Group Management Protocol, is used to manage the delivery of multicast streams to the groups of recipients on a LAN.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] One of the challenges in deploying IP multicast is that routers and firewalls between LANs must allow the passage of packets destined to multicast groups.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Peer-to-peer (P2P) protocols arrange for prerecorded streams to be sent between computers.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] This prevents the server and its network connections from becoming a bottleneck.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] However, it raises technical, performance, security, quality, and business issues.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Content delivery networks (CDNs) use intermediate servers to distribute the load.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Internet-compatible unicast delivery is used between CDN nodes and streaming destinations.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Media that is livestreamed can be recorded through certain media players, such as VLC player, or through the use of a screen recorder.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Live-streaming platforms such as Twitch may also incorporate a video on demand system that allows automatic recording of live broadcasts so that they can be watched later.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] YouTube also has recordings of live broadcasts, including television shows aired on major networks.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] These streams have the potential to be recorded by anyone who has access to them, whether legally or otherwise.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Recordings can happen through any device that allows people to watch movies they do not have access to or be at a music festival they could not get tickets to.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] These live streaming platforms have revolutionized entertainment, creating new ways for people to interact with content.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Many celebrities started live streaming during COVID-19 through platforms like Instagram, YouTube, and TikTok offering an alternate form of entertainment when concerts were postponed.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Live streaming and recording allow for fans to communicate with these artists through chats and likes.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Most streaming services feature a recommender system for viewing based on each user's view history in conjunction with all viewers' aggregated view histories.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Useful and typical applications of streaming are, for example, long video lectures performed online.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] An advantage of this presentation is that these lectures can be very long, although they can always be interrupted or repeated at arbitrary places.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Streaming enables new content marketing concepts.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] For example, the Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra sells Internet live streams of whole concerts instead of several CDs or similar fixed media in their Digital Concert Hall using YouTube for trailers.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] These online concerts are also spread over a lot of different places, including cinemas at various places on the globe.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] A similar concept is used by the Metropolitan Opera in New York.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] There is also a livestream from the International Space Station.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] In video entertainment, video streaming platforms like Netflix, Hulu, and Disney+ are mainstream elements of the media industry.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Marketers have found many opportunities offered by streaming media and the platforms that offer them, especially in light of the significant increase in the use of streaming media during COVID lockdowns from 2020 onwards.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] While revenue and placement of traditional advertising continued to decrease, digital marketing increased by 15% in 2021, with digital media and search representing 65% of the expenditures.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] A case study commissioned by the WIPO indicates that streaming services attract advertising budgets with the opportunities provided by interactivity and the use of data from users, resulting in personalization on a mass scale with content marketing.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Targeted marketing is expanding with the use of artificial intelligence, in particular programmatic advertisement, a tool that helps advertisers decide their campaign parameters and whether they are interested in buying advertising space online or not.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] One example of advertising space acquisition is Real-Time Bidding (RTB).
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] For over-the-top media service (OTT) platforms, the original content captures additional subscribers.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] This presents copyright issues and the potential for international exploitation through streaming, widespread use of standards, and metadata in digital files.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The WIPO has indicated several basic copyright issues arising for those pursuing work in the film and music industries in the era of streaming.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Streaming copyrighted content can involve making infringing copies of the works in question.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The recording and distribution of streamed content is also an issue for many companies that rely on revenue based on views or attendance.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The net greenhouse gas emissions from streaming music were estimated at between 0.2 and 0.35 million metric tons CO2eq (between 200,000 and 340,000 long tons; 220,000 and 390,000 short tons) per year in the United States, by a 2019 study.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] For example greenhouse gas emissions in the United States from beef cattle (burping of ruminants only - not including their manure) were 129 million metric tons (127 million long tons; 142 million short tons) in 2019.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] However, another study estimated a relatively low amount of 36 grams per hour (1.3 ounces per hour), and concluded that watching a Netflix video for half an hour emitted only the same amount as driving a gasoline-fuelled car for about 100 meters (330 ft), so not a significant amount.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] One way to decrease greenhouse gas emissions associated with streaming music is to make data centers carbon neutral by converting to electricity produced from renewable sources.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] On an individual level, the purchase of a physical CD may be more environmentally friendly if it is to be played more than 27 times.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] Another option for reducing energy use is downloading the music for offline listening to reduce the need for streaming over distance.
[src:rtp-streaming/streaming-media] The Spotify service has a built-in local cache to reduce the necessity of repeating song streams.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP technology has evolved to integrate with mobile telephony, including Voice over LTE (VoLTE) and Voice over NR (Vo5G), enabling seamless voice communication over mobile data networks.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] These advancements have extended VoIP's role beyond its traditional use in Internet-based applications.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] It has become a key component of modern mobile infrastructure, as 4G and 5G networks rely entirely on this technology for voice transmission.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The steps and principles involved in originating VoIP telephone calls are similar to traditional digital telephony and involve signaling, channel setup, digitization of the analog voice signals, and encoding.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Instead of being transmitted over a circuit-switched network, the digital information is packetized and transmission occurs as IP packets over a packet-switched network.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] They transport media streams using special media delivery protocols that encode audio and video with audio codecs and video codecs.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Various codecs exist that optimize the media stream based on application requirements and network bandwidth; some implementations rely on narrowband and compressed speech, while others support high-fidelity stereo codecs.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The most widely used speech coding standards in VoIP are based on the linear predictive coding (LPC) and modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) compression methods.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Popular codecs include the MDCT-based AAC-LD (used in FaceTime), the LPC/MDCT-based Opus (used in WhatsApp), the LPC-based SILK (used in Skype), μ-law, A-law versions of G.711, G.722, an open source voice codec known as iLBC, and a codec that uses only 8 kbit/s each way called G.729.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Early providers of voice-over-IP services used business models and offered technical solutions that mirrored the architecture of the legacy telephone network.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Second-generation providers, such as Skype, built closed networks for private user bases, offering the benefit of free calls and convenience while potentially charging for access to other communication networks, such as the PSTN.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] This limited the freedom of users to mix-and-match third-party hardware and software.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Third-generation providers, such as Google Talk, adopted the concept of federated VoIP.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] These solutions typically allow dynamic interconnection between users in any two domains of the Internet, when a user wishes to place a call.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In addition to VoIP phones, VoIP is also available on many personal computers and other Internet access devices.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Calls and SMS text messages may be sent via Wi-Fi or the carrier's mobile data network.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP provides a framework for consolidation of all modern communications technologies using a single unified communications system.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP technology has been adapted for use in mobile networks, leading to the development of advanced systems designed to support voice communication over modern data infrastructures.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Among these are Voice over LTE (VoLTE) and Voice over 5G (Vo5G), which enable voice communication over IP-based mobile infrastructures.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In contrast to traditional VoIP services, which often function independently of global telephone numbering systems, VoLTE and Vo5G are directly connected to mobile operators' infrastructures, providing seamless connectivity to the international telephone network.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoLTE, introduced as part of 4G LTE networks, enables voice communication over an IP-based infrastructure initially developed for data transmission.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] It offers features such as high-definition voice (HD Voice) and faster call setup times compared to circuit-switched networks.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Vo5G, the 5G equivalent of VoLTE, utilizes the increased speed, reduced latency, and greater capacity of 5G networks to further enhance these capabilities.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Both VoLTE and Vo5G maintain compatibility with traditional public switched telephone networks (PSTNs), allowing users to make and receive calls to and from any telephone number worldwide.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] These technologies differ from standalone VoIP services by being fully integrated with mobile network operators.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] This integration ensures additional features such as emergency call support and quality-of-service guarantees, making them a central part of modern mobile telecommunication systems.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Voice over IP has been implemented with proprietary protocols and protocols based on open standards in applications such as VoIP phones, mobile applications, and web-based communications.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] A variety of functions are needed to implement VoIP communication.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Some protocols perform multiple functions, while others perform only a few and must be used in concert.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Mass-market VoIP services use existing broadband Internet access, by which subscribers place and receive telephone calls in much the same manner as they would via the PSTN.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Full-service VoIP phone companies provide inbound and outbound service with direct inbound dialing.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Many offer unlimited domestic calling and sometimes international calls for a flat monthly subscription fee.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Phone calls between subscribers of the same provider are usually free when flat-fee service is not available.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] A VoIP phone is necessary to connect to a VoIP service provider.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] It is increasingly common for telecommunications providers to use VoIP telephony over dedicated and public IP networks as a backhaul to connect switching centers and to interconnect with other telephony network providers; this is often referred to as *IP backhaul*.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Smartphones may have SIP clients built into the firmware or available as an application download.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Because of the bandwidth efficiency and low costs that VoIP technology can provide, businesses are migrating from traditional copper-wire telephone systems to VoIP systems to reduce their monthly phone costs.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In 2008, 80% of all new Private branch exchange (PBX) lines installed internationally were VoIP.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] For example, in the United States, the Social Security Administration is converting its field offices of 63,000 workers from traditional phone installations to a VoIP infrastructure carried over its existing data network.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP allows both voice and data communications to be run over a single network, which can significantly reduce infrastructure costs.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The prices of extensions on VoIP are lower than for PBX and key systems.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP switches may run on commodity hardware, such as personal computers.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Rather than closed architectures, these devices rely on standard interfaces.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP devices have simple, intuitive user interfaces, so users can often make simple system configuration changes.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Dual-mode phones enable users to continue their conversations as they move between an outside cellular service and an internal Wi-Fi network, so that it is no longer necessary to carry both a desktop phone and a cell phone.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Maintenance becomes simpler as there are fewer devices to oversee.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP solutions aimed at businesses have evolved into unified communications services that treat all communications—phone calls, faxes, voice mail, e-mail, web conferences, and more—as discrete units that can all be delivered via any means and to any handset, including cellphones.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Two kinds of service providers are operating in this space: one set is focused on VoIP for medium to large enterprises, while another is targeting the small-to-medium business (SMB) market.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Skype, which originally marketed itself as a service among friends, began to cater to businesses in 2009, providing free-of-charge connections between any users on the Skype network and connecting to and from ordinary PSTN telephones for a charge.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In general, the provision of VoIP telephony systems to organizational or individual users can be divided into two primary delivery methods: private or on-premises solutions, or externally hosted solutions delivered by third-party providers.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] On-premises delivery methods are more akin to the classic PBX deployment model for connecting an office to local PSTN networks.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] While many use cases still remain for private or on-premises VoIP systems, the wider market has been gradually shifting toward *Cloud* or *Hosted* VoIP solutions.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Hosted systems are also generally better suited to smaller or personal use VoIP deployments, where a private system may not be viable for these scenarios.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Typically, this will be one or more data centers with geographic relevance to the end-user(s) of the system.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] This infrastructure is external to the user of the system and is deployed and maintained by the service provider.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Endpoints, such as VoIP telephones or softphone applications (apps running on a computer or mobile device), will connect to the VoIP service remotely.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] These connections typically take place over public internet links, such as local fixed WAN breakout or mobile carrier service.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In the case of a private VoIP system, the primary telephony system itself is located within the private infrastructure of the end-user organization.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Usually, the system will be deployed on-premises at a site within the direct control of the organization.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] This can provide numerous benefits in terms of QoS control (see below), cost scalability, and ensuring privacy and security of communications traffic.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] However, the responsibility for ensuring that the VoIP system remains performant and resilient is predominantly vested in the end-user organization.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] This is not the case with a Hosted VoIP solution.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Private VoIP systems can be physical hardware PBX appliances, converged with other infrastructure, or they can be deployed as software applications.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Generally, the latter two options will be in the form of a separate virtualized appliance.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] However, in some scenarios, these systems are deployed on bare metal infrastructure or IoT devices.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] With some solutions, such as 3CX, companies can attempt to blend the benefits of hosted and private on-premises systems by implementing their own private solution but within an external environment.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Examples can include data center collocation services, public cloud, or private cloud locations.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] For on-premises systems, local endpoints within the same location typically connect directly over the LAN.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] For remote and external endpoints, available connectivity options mirror those of Hosted or Cloud VoIP solutions.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] However, VoIP traffic to and from the on-premises systems can often also be sent over secure private links.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Examples include personal VPN, site-to-site VPN, private networks such as MPLS and SD-WAN, or via private SBCs (Session Border Controllers).
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] While exceptions and private peering options do exist, it is generally uncommon for those private connectivity methods to be provided by Hosted or Cloud VoIP providers.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Communication on the IP network is perceived as less reliable in contrast to the circuit-switched public telephone network because it does not provide a network-based mechanism to ensure that data packets are not lost, and are delivered in sequential order.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] It is a best-effort network without fundamental quality of service (QoS) guarantees.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Voice, and all other data, travels in packets over IP networks with fixed maximum capacity.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Therefore, VoIP implementations may face problems with latency, packet loss, and jitter.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] By default, network routers handle traffic on a first-come, first-served basis.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Fixed delays cannot be controlled as they are caused by the physical distance the packets travel.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] They are especially problematic when satellite circuits are involved because of the long distance to a geostationary satellite and back; delays of 400–600 ms are typical.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Latency can be minimized by marking voice packets as being delay-sensitive with QoS methods such as DiffServ.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Network routers on high-volume traffic links may introduce latency that exceeds permissible thresholds for VoIP.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Excessive load on a link can cause congestion and associated queueing delays and packet loss.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] This signals a transport protocol like TCP to reduce its transmission rate to alleviate the congestion.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] But VoIP usually uses UDP, not TCP, because recovering from congestion through retransmission usually entails too much latency.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] So QoS mechanisms can avoid the undesirable loss of VoIP packets by immediately transmitting them ahead of any queued bulk traffic on the same link, even when the link is congested by bulk traffic.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP endpoints usually have to wait for the completion of transmission of previous packets before new data may be sent.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Although it is possible to preempt (abort) a less important packet in mid-transmission, this is not commonly done, especially on high-speed links where transmission times are short even for maximum-sized packets.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] An alternative to preemption on slower links, such as dialup and digital subscriber line (DSL), is to reduce the maximum transmission time by reducing the maximum transmission unit.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] But since every packet must contain protocol headers, this increases relative header overhead on every link traversed.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The receiver must resequence IP packets that arrive out of order and recover gracefully when packets arrive too late or not at all.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Packet delay variation results from changes in queuing delay along a given network path due to competition from other users for the same transmission links.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP receivers accommodate this variation by storing incoming packets briefly in a playout buffer, deliberately increasing latency to improve the chance that each packet will be on hand when it is time for the voice engine to play it.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The added delay is thus a compromise between excessive latency and excessive dropout, i.e., momentary audio interruptions.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Although jitter is a random variable, it is the sum of several other random variables that are at least somewhat independent: the individual queuing delays of the routers along the Internet path in question.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Motivated by the central limit theorem, jitter can be modeled as a Gaussian random variable.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] This suggests continually estimating the mean delay and its standard deviation and setting the playout delay so that only packets delayed more than several standard deviations above the mean will arrive too late to be useful.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In practice, the variance in latency of many Internet paths is dominated by a small number (often one) of relatively slow and congested bottleneck links.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Most Internet backbone links are now so fast (e.g., 10 Gbit/s) that their delays are dominated by the transmission medium (e.g., optical fiber) and the routers driving them do not have enough buffering for queuing delays to be significant.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] A number of protocols have been defined to support the reporting of quality of service (QoS) and quality of experience (QoE) for VoIP calls.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] These include RTP Control Protocol (RTCP) extended reports, SIP RTCP summary reports, H.460.9 Annex B (for H.323), H.248.30 and MGCP extensions.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP metrics reports are exchanged between IP endpoints on an occasional basis during a call, and an end-of-call message is sent via SIP RTCP summary report or one of the other signaling protocol extensions.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP metrics reports are intended to support real-time feedback related to QoS problems, the exchange of information between the endpoints for improved call quality calculation and a variety of other applications.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] DSL modems typically provide Ethernet connections to local equipment, but inside they may actually be Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) modems.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] They use ATM Adaptation Layer 5 (AAL5) to segment each Ethernet packet into a series of 53-byte ATM cells for transmission, reassembling them back into Ethernet frames at the receiving end.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Using a separate virtual circuit identifier (VCI) for voice over IP has the potential to reduce latency on shared connections.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] ATM's potential for latency reduction is greatest on slow links because worst-case latency decreases with increasing link speed.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] A full-size (1500 byte) Ethernet frame takes 94 ms to transmit at 128 kbit/s but only 8 ms at 1.5 Mbit/s.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] If this is the bottleneck link, this latency is probably small enough to ensure good VoIP performance without MTU reductions or multiple ATM VCs.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The latest generations of DSL, VDSL and VDSL2, carry Ethernet without intermediate ATM/AAL5 layers, and they generally support IEEE 802.1p priority tagging so that VoIP can be queued ahead of less time-critical traffic.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] ATM has substantial header overhead: 5/53 = 9.4%, roughly twice the total header overhead of a 1500-byte Ethernet frame.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] This *ATM tax* is incurred by every DSL user, whether or not they take advantage of multiple virtual circuits – and few can.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Several protocols are used in the data link layer and physical layer for quality-of-service mechanisms that help VoIP applications work well even in the presence of network congestion.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The quality of voice transmission is characterized by several metrics that may be monitored by network elements and by the user agent hardware or software.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Such metrics include network packet loss, packet jitter, packet latency (delay), post-dial delay, and echo.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The metrics are determined by VoIP performance testing and monitoring.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] A VoIP media gateway controller (aka Class 5 Softswitch) works in cooperation with a media gateway (aka IP Business Gateway) and connects the digital media stream, so as to complete the path for voice and data.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Gateways include interfaces for connecting to standard PSTN networks.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Ethernet interfaces are also included in modern systems, which are specially designed to link calls that are passed via VoIP.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] E.164 is a global numbering standard for both the PSTN and public land mobile network (PLMN).
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Most VoIP implementations support E.164 to allow calls to be routed to and from VoIP subscribers and the PSTN/PLMN.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP implementations can also allow other identification techniques to be used.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] For example, Skype allows subscribers to choose *Skype names* (usernames) whereas SIP implementations can use Uniform Resource Identifier (URIs) similar to email addresses.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Often VoIP implementations employ methods of translating non-E.164 identifiers to E.164 numbers and vice versa, such as the Skype-In service provided by Skype and the E.164 number to URI mapping (ENUM) service in IMS and SIP.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Echo can also be an issue for PSTN integration.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Common causes of echo include impedance mismatches in analog circuitry and an acoustic path from the receive to transmit signal at the receiving end.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Local number portability (LNP) and mobile number portability (MNP) also impact VoIP business.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Number portability is a service that allows a subscriber to select a new telephone carrier without requiring a new number to be issued.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Typically, it is the responsibility of the former carrier to "map" the old number to the undisclosed number assigned by the new carrier.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] This is achieved by maintaining a database of numbers.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] A dialed number is initially received by the original carrier and quickly rerouted to the new carrier.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Multiple porting references must be maintained even if the subscriber returns to the original carrier.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) mandates carrier compliance with these consumer-protection stipulations.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In November 2007, the FCC in the United States released an order extending number portability obligations to interconnected VoIP providers and carriers that support VoIP providers.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] A voice call originating in the VoIP environment also faces least-cost routing (LCR) challenges to reach its destination if the number is routed to a mobile phone number on a traditional mobile carrier.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] LCR is based on checking the destination of each telephone call as it is made, and then sending the call via the network that will cost the customer the least.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] This rating is subject to some debate, given the complexity of call routing created by number portability.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] With MNP in place, LCR providers can no longer rely on using the network root prefix to determine how to route a call.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Instead, they must now determine the actual network of every number before routing the call.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Therefore, VoIP solutions also need to handle MNP when routing a voice call.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In countries without a central database, like the UK, it may be necessary to query the mobile network about which home network a mobile phone number belongs to.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] As the popularity of VoIP increases in the enterprise markets because of LCR options, VoIP needs to provide a certain level of reliability when handling calls.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] A telephone connected to a land line has a direct relationship between a telephone number and a physical location, which is maintained by the telephone company and available to emergency responders via the national emergency response service centers in the form of emergency subscriber lists.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] When an emergency call is received by a center, the location is automatically determined from its databases and displayed on the operator console.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In IP telephony, no such direct link between location and communications end point exists.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Even a provider having wired infrastructure, such as a DSL provider, may know only the approximate location of the device, based on the IP address allocated to the network router and the known service address.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Some ISPs do not track the automatic assignment of IP addresses to customer equipment.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] IP communication provides for device mobility.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] For example, a residential broadband connection may be used as a link to a virtual private network of a corporate entity, in which case the IP address being used for customer communications may belong to the enterprise, not the residential ISP.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Such off-premises extensions may appear as part of an upstream IP PBX.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] On mobile devices, e.g., a 3G handset or USB wireless broadband adapter, the IP address has no relationship with any physical location known to the telephony service provider, since a mobile user could be anywhere in a region with network coverage, even roaming via another cellular company.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] At the VoIP level, a phone or gateway may identify itself by its account credentials with a Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) registrar.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In such cases, the Internet telephony service provider (ITSP) knows only that a particular user's equipment is active.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Service providers often provide emergency response services by agreement with the user who registers a physical location and agrees that, if an emergency number is called from the IP device, emergency services are provided to that address only.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Such emergency services are provided by VoIP vendors in the United States by a system called Enhanced 911 (E911), based on the Wireless Communications and Public Safety Act.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The VoIP E911 emergency-calling system associates a physical address with the calling party's telephone number.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] All VoIP providers that provide access to the public switched telephone network are required to implement E911, a service for which the subscriber may be charged.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] "VoIP providers may not allow customers to opt out of 911 service." The VoIP E911 system is based on a static table lookup.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Unlike in cellular phones, where the location of an E911 call can be traced using assisted GPS or other methods, the VoIP E911 information is accurate only if subscribers keep their emergency address information current.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Sending faxes over VoIP networks is sometimes referred to as Fax over IP (FoIP).
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Transmission of fax documents was problematic in early VoIP implementations, as most voice digitization and compression codecs are optimized for the representation of the human voice and the proper timing of the modem signals cannot be guaranteed in a packet-based, connectionless network.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] A standards-based solution for reliably delivering fax-over-IP is the T.38 protocol.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The T.38 protocol is designed to compensate for the differences between traditional packet-less communications over analog lines and packet-based transmissions, which are the basis for IP communications.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The fax machine may be a standard device connected to an analog telephone adapter (ATA), or it may be a software application or dedicated network device operating via an Ethernet interface.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Originally, T.38 was designed to use UDP or TCP transmission methods across an IP network.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Some newer high-end fax machines have built-in T.38 capabilities, which are connected directly to a network switch or router.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In T.38 each packet contains a portion of the data stream sent in the previous packet.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Two successive packets have to be lost to actually lose data integrity.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Telephones for traditional residential analog service are usually connected directly to telephone company phone lines, which provide direct current to power most basic analog handsets independently of locally available electrical power.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP phones and VoIP telephone adapters connect to routers or cable modems, which typically depend on the availability of mains electricity or locally generated power.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Some VoIP service providers use customer premises equipment (e.g., cable modems) with battery-backed power supplies to assure uninterrupted service for up to several hours in case of local power failures.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Such battery-backed devices are typically designed for use with analog handsets.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Some VoIP service providers implement services to route calls to other telephone services of the subscriber, such as a cellular phone, in the event that the customer's network device is inaccessible to terminate the call.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Secure calls are possible using standardized protocols such as Secure Real-time Transport Protocol.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Most of the facilities for creating a secure telephone connection over traditional phone lines, such as digitizing and digital transmission, are already in place with VoIP.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] It is necessary only to encrypt and authenticate the existing data stream.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Automated software, such as a virtual PBX, may eliminate the need for personnel to greet and switch incoming calls.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The security concerns for VoIP telephone systems are similar to those of other Internet-connected devices.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] This means that hackers with knowledge of VoIP vulnerabilities can perform denial-of-service attacks, harvest customer data, record conversations, and compromise voicemail messages.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Compromised VoIP user account or session credentials may enable an attacker to incur substantial charges from third-party services, such as long-distance or international calling.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The technical details of many VoIP protocols create challenges in routing VoIP traffic through firewalls and network address translators, used to interconnect to transit networks or the Internet.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Private session border controllers are often employed to enable VoIP calls to and from protected networks.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Other methods to traverse NAT devices involve assistive protocols such as STUN and Interactive Connectivity Establishment (ICE).
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Standards for securing VoIP are available in the Secure Real-time Transport Protocol (SRTP) and the ZRTP protocol for analog telephony adapters, as well as for some softphones.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] IPsec is available to secure point-to-point VoIP at the transport level by using opportunistic encryption.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Though many consumer VoIP solutions do not support encryption of the signaling path or the media, securing a VoIP phone is conceptually easier to implement using VoIP than on traditional telephone circuits.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] A result of the lack of widespread support for encryption is that it is relatively easy to eavesdrop on VoIP calls when access to the data network is possible.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Free open-source solutions, such as Wireshark, facilitate capturing VoIP conversations.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Government and military organizations use various security measures to protect VoIP traffic, such as voice over secure IP (VoSIP), secure voice over IP (SVoIP), and secure voice over secure IP (SVoSIP).
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The distinction lies in whether encryption is applied in the telephone endpoint or in the network.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Secure voice over secure IP may be implemented by encrypting the media with protocols such as SRTP and ZRTP.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Secure voice over IP uses Type 1 encryption on a classified network, such as SIPRNet.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Public Secure VoIP is also available with free GNU software and in many popular commercial VoIP programs via libraries, such as ZRTP.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In June 2021, the National Security Agency (NSA) released comprehensive documents describing the four attack planes of a communications system – the network, perimeter, session controllers and endpoints – and explaining security risks and mitigation techniques for each of them.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Voice over IP protocols and equipment provide caller ID support that is compatible with the PSTN.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Many VoIP service providers also allow callers to configure custom caller ID information.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Wireline telephones which are manufactured in, imported to, or intended to be used in the US with Voice over IP service, on or after February 28, 2020, are required to meet the hearing aid compatibility requirements set forth by the Federal Communications Commission.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP has drastically reduced the cost of communication by sharing network infrastructure between data and voice.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] A single broadband connection has the ability to transmit multiple telephone calls.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] As the popularity of VoIP grows, governments are becoming more interested in regulating VoIP in a manner similar to PSTN services.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Throughout the developing world, particularly in countries where regulation is weak or captured by the dominant operator, restrictions on the use of VoIP are often imposed, including in Panama where VoIP is taxed, Guyana, where VoIP is prohibited.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In Ethiopia, where the government is nationalizing telecommunication service, it is a criminal offense to offer services using VoIP.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The country has installed firewalls to prevent international calls from being made using VoIP.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] These measures were taken after the popularity of VoIP reduced the income generated by the state-owned telecommunications company.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In Canada, the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission regulates telephone service, including VoIP telephony service.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP services operating in Canada are required to provide 9-1-1 emergency service.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] A general distinction is usually made between VoIP services that function over managed networks (via broadband connections) and VoIP services that function over unmanaged networks (essentially, the Internet).
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The relevant EU Directive is not clearly drafted concerning obligations that can exist independently of market power (e.g., the obligation to offer access to emergency calls), and it is impossible to say definitively whether VoIP service providers of either type are bound by them.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In Oman, it is illegal to provide or use unauthorized VoIP services, to the extent that websites of unlicensed VoIP providers have been blocked.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Violations may be punished with fines of 50,000 Omani Rial (about 130,317 US dollars), a two-year prison sentence or both.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In 2009, police raided 121 Internet cafes throughout the country and arrested 212 people for using or providing VoIP services.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In September 2017, Saudi Arabia lifted the ban on VoIPs, in an attempt to reduce operational costs and spur digital entrepreneurship.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In the United Arab Emirates (UAE), it is illegal to provide or use unauthorized VoIP services.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Websites of unlicensed VoIP providers have been blocked.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Some VoIP services, such as Skype, were allowed.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In January 2018, internet service providers in UAE blocked all VoIP apps, including Skype, but permitting only 2 government-approved VoIP apps (C'ME and BOTIM).
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In opposition, a petition on *Change.org* garnered over 5000 signatures, in response to which the website was blocked in UAE.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] On March 24, 2020, the United Arab Emirates loosened restrictions on VoIP services earlier prohibited in the country, to ease communication during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] However, popular instant messaging applications such as WhatsApp, Skype, and FaceTime remained blocked from being used for voice and video calls, constricting residents to use paid services from the country's state-owned telecom providers.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In India, it is legal to use VoIP, but it is illegal to have VoIP gateways inside India.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] This effectively means that people who have PCs can use them to make a VoIP call to other computers but not to a normal phone number.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Foreign-based VoIP server services are illegal to use in India.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Internet telephony is permitted to the ISP with restrictions.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] PC / a device / Adapter conforming to the standard of any international agencies like ITU or IETF, etc., in India to PSTN/PLMN abroad.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Any device / Adapter conforming to standards of International agencies like ITU, IETF etc., connected to ISP node with static IP address to similar device / Adapter; within or outside India.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Except whatever is described in condition (ii) above, no other form of Internet Telephony is permitted.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In India no Separate Numbering Scheme is provided to the Internet Telephony.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Presently the 10-digit Numbering allocation based on E.164 is permitted to the Fixed Telephony, GSM, CDMA wireless service.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] For Internet Telephony, the numbering scheme shall only conform to IP addressing Scheme of Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA).
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Translation of E.164 number / private number to IP address allotted to any device and vice versa, by ISP to show compliance with IANA numbering scheme is not permitted.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The Internet Service Licensee is not permitted to have PSTN/PLMN connectivity.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Voice communication to and from a telephone connected to PSTN/PLMN and following E.164 numbering is prohibited in India.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In South Korea, only providers registered with the government are authorized to offer VoIP services.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Unlike many VoIP providers, most of whom offer flat rates, Korean VoIP services are generally metered and charged at rates similar to terrestrial calling.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Foreign VoIP providers encounter high barriers to government registration.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] In the United States, the FCC requires all interconnected VoIP service providers to comply with requirements comparable to those for traditional telecommunications service providers.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP operators also receive the benefit of certain US telecommunications regulations, including an entitlement to interconnection and exchange of traffic with incumbent local exchange carriers via wholesale carriers.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Providers of *nomadic* VoIP service—those who are unable to determine the location of their users—are exempt from state telecommunications regulation.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] Another legal issue that the US Congress is debating concerns changes to the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The issue in question is calls between Americans and foreigners.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] The NSA is not authorized to tap Americans' conversations without a warrant—but the Internet, and specifically VoIP does not draw as clear a line to the location of a caller or a call's recipient as the traditional phone system does.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] As VoIP's low cost and flexibility convince more and more organizations to adopt the technology, surveillance for law enforcement agencies becomes more difficult.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP technology has also increased federal security concerns because VoIP and similar technologies have made it more difficult for the government to determine where a target is physically located when communications are being intercepted, and that creates a whole set of new legal challenges.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p02] Danny Cohen first demonstrated a form of packet voice in 1973 which was developed into Network Voice Protocol which operated across the early ARPANET.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p02] On the early ARPANET, real-time voice communication was not possible with uncompressed pulse-code modulation (PCM) digital speech packets, which had a bit rate of 64 kbps, much greater than the 2.4 kbps bandwidth of early modems.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p02] The solution to this problem was linear predictive coding (LPC), a speech coding data compression algorithm that was first proposed by Fumitada Itakura of Nagoya University and Shuzo Saito of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone (NTT) in 1966.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p02] LPC was capable of speech compression down to 2.4 kbps, leading to the first successful real-time conversation over ARPANET in 1974, between Culler-Harrison Incorporated in Goleta, California, and MIT Lincoln Laboratory in Lexington, Massachusetts.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p02] LPC has since been the most widely used speech coding method.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p02] Code-excited linear prediction (CELP), a type of LPC algorithm, was developed by Manfred R.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p02] LPC algorithms remain an audio coding standard in modern VoIP technology.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p02] In the two decades following the 1974 demo, various forms of packet telephony were developed and industry interest groups formed to support the new technologies.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p02] Soon after it became an established area of interest in commercial labs of the major IT concerns, notably at AT&T, where Marian Croak and her team filed many patents related to the technology.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p02] By the late 1990s, the first softswitches became available, and new protocols, such as H.323, MGCP and Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) gained widespread attention.
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p02] In the early 2000s, the proliferation of high-bandwidth always-on Internet connections to residential dwellings and businesses spawned an industry of Internet telephony service providers (ITSPs).
[src:rtp-streaming/voice-over-ip-p02] The development of open-source telephony software, such as Asterisk PBX, fueled widespread interest and entrepreneurship in voice-over-IP services, applying new Internet technology paradigms, such as cloud services to telephony.
